i have installed flask two times

Ah! That explains the confusion ‚Äî you probably installed Flask once in the global Python environment and once in the virtual environment.

Here‚Äôs what‚Äôs happening:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Global vs Virtual Environment

Global Python: python3 -m pip install flask
This installs Flask system-wide. If you run python3 app.py without activating .venv, it uses this global Python. If Flask wasn‚Äôt installed globally, you‚Äôd get the ModuleNotFoundError.

Virtual Environment (.venv): source .venv/bin/activate ‚Üí pip install flask
Flask is installed only inside this virtual environment. When .venv is active, running python app.py works perfectly.

üí° So installing Flask globally is unnecessary if you always use a virtual environment ‚Äî the venv is all you need.

2Ô∏è‚É£ What You Should Do

Always activate the virtual environment before running your app:

source ~/Downloads/python/.venv/bin/activate
python app.py


Or, if you don‚Äôt want to activate each time, run:

~/Downloads/python/.venv/bin/python app.py


You can uninstall the global Flask if you want, to avoid confusion:

python3 -m pip uninstall flask

3Ô∏è‚É£ Why You Got the Error Now

When you opened a new terminal, you ran:

python3 app.py


Without activating .venv, your system Python doesn‚Äôt see Flask.

Flask exists only in .venv, so Python complains: ModuleNotFoundError.

If you want, I can give you a single command to always run your Flask app correctly, even in a new terminal, so you never have to worry about which environment is active. It‚Äôs a neat trick many developers use.

Do you want me to do that?


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------



ok i have installed flask globally 

Got it! If Flask is now installed globally, your system Python should be able to run your app without activating a virtual environment.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Test Global Flask

Run:

python3 -m pip show flask


You should see something like:

Name: Flask
Version: 3.x.x
Location: /usr/local/lib/python3.x/dist-packages


Then try running your app:

python3 app.py


You should see:

 * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000
 * Debug mode: on

2Ô∏è‚É£ Notes About Global vs Virtual Environment

Global installation works fine, but it has downsides:

Different projects may need different Flask versions, which can conflict.

Upgrading or uninstalling Flask globally affects all projects using it.

Virtual environment (.venv) isolates packages per project. Recommended for development.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Optional: Stick to Virtual Environment (Cleaner)

Even though Flask is installed globally, it‚Äôs cleaner to use .venv. Then you don‚Äôt worry about conflicts.

Steps:

# Activate your venv
source ~/Downloads/python/.venv/bin/activate

# Install Flask inside venv
pip install flask

# Run your app
python app.py


üí° Summary:

Globally installed Flask ‚Üí works system-wide.

Virtual environment Flask ‚Üí isolated, safer for multiple projects.
